Going from the lowest to the highest multiplicity events, the relative increase of {\ensuremath{\langle p_{\mathrm{T}}\rangle}}~for {\ensuremath{{\rm K}^{*0}}}~and {\ensuremath{\phi}}~mesons is about 40$\%$, common to a wide variety of particles, including K$^{\pm}$, K$^{0}_{S}$, $\Lambda$, $\Xi^{\pm}$ and $\Omega^{\pm}$. 
The relative increase is smaller for {\ensuremath{\pi}}~(about 26$\%$) but larger for protons (about 52$\%$). 
The {\ensuremath{\langle p_{\mathrm{T}}\rangle}}~of {\ensuremath{{\rm K}^{*0}}}~is about 10$\%$ larger than that of proton in all event classes and compatible with {\ensuremath{\langle p_{\mathrm{T}}\rangle}}~of $\Lambda$. The {\ensuremath{\langle p_{\mathrm{T}}\rangle}}~of {\ensuremath{\phi}}~is instead about 20$\%$ larger than proton and between 4$\%$ (0--5$\%$) and 8$\%$ (80--100$\%$) larger than $\Lambda$. A similar hierarchy is also observed in pp collisions and peripheral {\ensuremath{\mbox{Pb--Pb}}}~collisions, but not in central {\ensuremath{\mbox{Pb--Pb}}}~collisions, where, as expected from hydrodynamics, particles with similar mass have similar {\ensuremath{\langle p_{\mathrm{T}}\rangle}}. 

